Laboratory near Santa Fe, New Mexico

For the World War II-era laboratory in Los Alamos, see [Los Alamos Laboratory](/Los_Alamos_Laboratory).

---

### Los Alamos National Laboratory

• LANL

[[File:Los Alamos National Laboratory aerial view.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the [Los Alamos National Laboratory](/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory)]]

Consider it the birthplace of modern existential dread, neatly packaged with a side of scientific marvel. The [Los Alamos National Laboratory](/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory), often referred to simply as Los Alamos or by its rather uninspired acronym, LANL, stands as one of the sixteen behemoths in the research and development portfolio of the [United States Department of Energy (DOE)](/United_States_Department_of_Energy_National_Laboratories). Its geographical footprint graces the landscape a mere stone's throw — if you happen to throw stones with strategic intent — northwest of [Santa Fe, New Mexico](/Santa_Fe,_New_Mexico), nestled firmly within the [American southwest](/Southwestern_United_States).

This institution, established in the crucible of 1943, has, for better or worse, etched its name into the annals of history, primarily for its undeniably central, if ethically complex, role in ushering the [first atomic bomb](/First_Atomic_bomb) into existence. Today, it remains a colossal and remarkably advanced scientific enterprise, a testament to human ingenuity and its often terrifying applications. Its annual [budget](/Budget) hovers around a staggering $4.9 billion, a sum that might make even the most jaded among us pause.

The core fields of its research are as vast as they are critical, encompassing the grim necessities of [national security](/National_security) alongside the boundless pursuit of [fundamental science](/Fundamental_science). The current [Director](/Director_(business)) of this formidable establishment is [Thomas Mason](/Thomas_Mason_(physicist)). Supporting his oversight is a veritable army of intellect and labor: a [staff](/Employment) numbering 14,150, augmented by a transient population of 1800 [students](/Student), all diligently pushing the boundaries of what's possible, or perhaps, what's regrettable.

Located precisely at 35°52′32″N 106°19′27″W, in [Los Alamos](/Los_Alamos,_New_Mexico), [New Mexico](/New_Mexico), [United States](/United_States), the laboratory's operational structure is a fascinating blend of public ownership and private management. It is currently affiliated with a triumvirate of academic and corporate powerhouses: the esteemed [University of California](/University_of_California), the venerable [Battelle Memorial Institute](/Battelle_Memorial_Institute), and the sprawling [Texas A&M University](/Texas_A%26M_University). The day-to-day operations are entrusted to Triad National Security LLC, a consortium that presumably ensures the gears of scientific progress grind on, one way or another. For those who wish to peer into its digital soul, its official online presence can be found at https://www.lanl.gov/.

