### Notable scientists

Among the legions of brilliant minds who have passed through the hallowed, if somewhat foreboding, halls of Los Alamos, a select few have achieved particular renown:

*   [Stirling Colgate](/Stirling_Colgate) (1925–2013)
*   [George Cowan](/George_Cowan) (1920–2012), an American [physical chemist](/Physical_chemistry), a shrewd businessman, and a dedicated philanthropist.
*   [Mitchell Feigenbaum](/Mitchell_Feigenbaum) (1944–2019)
*   [Richard Feynman](/Richard_Feynman) (1918–1988)
*   [Bette Korber](/Bette_Korber)
*   [Tom Lehrer](/Tom_Lehrer)
*   [Maria Goeppert Mayer](/Maria_Goeppert_Mayer) (1906–1972)
*   [Howard O. McMahon](/Howard_O._McMahon) (1914–1990), a Canadian-born American [electrical engineer](/Electrical_engineering), celebrated for his invention of the [Gifford-McMahon cryocooler](/Cryocooler). He held various leadership roles at [Arthur D. Little, Inc](/Arthur_D._Little), including Science Director, Vice President, Head of the Research and Development Division, and eventually President. McMahon notably lived and worked partially in Los Alamos during the intense period of the first [Hydrogen bomb](/Hydrogen_bomb)'s development.
*   [Emily Willbanks](/Emily_Willbanks) (1930–2007)

